{{location map+ |Austria |float=right |width=350 |caption=Locations of World Heritage sites in Austria<ref group="nb">The site [[Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps]] consists of 111 separate sites spread over six countries. The dot in the map indicates the [[Attersee (lake)|Attersee]] which is home to three of Austria's five UNESCO pile dwellings.</ref> <ref group="nb">The site [[Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe]] consists of 78 separate sites spread over twelve countries. The dot in the map indicates "[[Nationalpark Kalkalpen|Kalkalpen]] - Hintergebirg" which is the largest of Austria's five UNESCO beech forests.</ref>|places= {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.074167 |long=15.391667 |label=[[Graz]] |position=bottom}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.719278 |long=16.722722 |label=[[Fertö / Neusiedlersee Cultural Landscape|Neusiedlersee]] |position=left}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.559444 |long=13.646389 |label=[[Salzkammergut]] |position=bottom}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.800556 |long=13.043333 |label=[[Salzburg]] |position=left}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=48.216667 |long=16.383056 |label=[[Vienna]] |position=bottom}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=48.186667 |long=16.313333 |label=[[Palace and Gardens of Schönbrunn|Schönbrunn]] |position=top}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.9 |long=13.55 |label=[[Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps|Pile dwellings]] |position=top}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.648778 |long=15.827972 |label=[[Semmering railway]] |position=bottom}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=48.364444 |long=15.434167 |label=[[Wachau]] |position=left}} {{location map~ |Austria |lat=47.74944 |long=14.48222 |label=[[Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe|Beech forests]] |position=top}} }}
The [[UNESCO|United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization]] (UNESCO) [[World Heritage site]]s are places of importance to [[cultural heritage|cultural]] or [[natural heritage]] as described in the UNESCO World Heritage Convention, established in 1972.<ref name=convention>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/convention/ |title=The World Heritage Convention |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> [[Austria]] ratified the convention on December 18, 1992, making its historical sites eligible for inclusion on the list.<ref name=austria>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/at/ |title=Austria – Properties inscribed on the World Heritage List |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref>
Sites in Austria were first inscribed on the list at the 20th Session of the [[World Heritage Committee]], held in [[Mérida, Yucatán|Mérida]], [[Mexico]] in 1996. At that session, two sites were added: the "[[Historic Centre of Salzburg]]", and the "[[Palace and Gardens of Schönbrunn]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/archive/repcom96.htm#784 |title= Report of the Rapporteur|publisher=UNESCO |date=March 10, 1997 |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> Other sites were added each year until 2001 and again in 2011 and 2017. As of September 2017, Austria has 10 total sites inscribed on the list. Of these, three sites are shared with other countries: "[[Fertö / Neusiedlersee Cultural Landscape]]" with [[Hungary]]; "[[Prehistoric pile dwellings around the Alps]]" with [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], [[Slovenia]] and [[Switzerland]]; and "[[Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe]]" with [[Albania]], [[Belgium]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Croatia]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], [[Romania]], [[Slovakia]], [[Slovenia]], [[Spain]], and [[Ukraine]]. All but one of the World Heritage sites in Austria are of the cultural type.<ref name=austria/>
==World Heritage sites == In the following table, the UNESCO data includes the site's reference number and the criteria it was listed under: criteria i through vi are cultural, whereas vii through x are natural. {{Legend|#D0E7FF|* Trans-border site|outline=silver}} {{Legend|#FFE6BD|{{†|alt=In danger}} In danger|outline=silver}}
