[[File:Salt lake-street.jpg|thumb|View from Rio Grande Street in Salt Lake City, Utah]]

'''Operation Rio Grande''' is the codename given to a massive multi-agency collaboration to promote public safety in the Rio Grande neighborhood of [[Salt Lake City]], Utah. It consists of three phases. Phase one was rolled out on August 14, 2017.<ref name="Utah Gov">{{cite web |title = Operation Rio Grande |url = http://operationriogrande.utah.gov/ |website = operationriogrande.utah.gov |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |language = en }}</ref> Phase one was targeted enforcement of laws. Phase two is rehabilitation of offenders who were arrested in phase one. Phase three will be to find jobs for all rehabilitated offenders. Its biggest impact is on Salt Lake's [[homelessness|homeless]] population, as the neighborhood has a very high density of homeless people and homeless services. The two year cost to fund the operation is estimated at {{US$|67{{nbsp}}million|link=yes}}.

== Details ==
Operation Rio Grande started its three phase rollout on August 14, 2017 in the Rio Grande neighborhood of Salt Lake City, Utah. The first phase was enforcement of laws. Part of the operation included an order from Salt Lake City Mayor Jackie Biskupski, shutting down Rio Grande Street permanently to vehicles and pedestrians to create a drug free zone.<ref name="SLCgov">{{cite web |last1 = Rojas |first1 = Matthew |title = Operation Rio Grande |url = http://www.slcgov.com/tags/operation-rio-grande |website = www.slcgov.com |publisher = SLCgov.com |accessdate = September 15, 2017 }}</ref> Mayor Biskupski stalled the closure for three weeks while she took public comment and went through city processes.<ref name="Closure Delay">{{cite news |last1 = Woodruff |first1 = Daniel |title = Tension erupts between House speaker, SLC mayor over Operation Rio Grande |url = http://kmyu.tv/news/local/tension-erupts-between-house-speaker-slc-mayor-over-operation-rio-grande |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = KMYU/KUTV |date = August 29, 2017 }}</ref> Utah state Governor Gary Herbert has called the state legislature into a special session to discuss the various aspects of the massive crackdown and intervention.<ref name="Special Session 2">{{cite news |last1 = McKellar |first1 = Katie |title = Herbert To Call Special Session To Deal With Operation Rio Grande Issues Next Week |url = https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865688709/Herbert-to-call-special-session-to-deal-with-Operation-Rio-Grande-issues-next-week.html |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = DeseretNews.com |date = September 13, 2017 |ref = Gov Herbert |language = en }}</ref><ref name="Biskupski">{{cite news |last1 = Winslow |first1 = Ben |title = Governor to call special session on 'Operation Rio Grande' issues next week |url = http://fox13now.com/2017/09/13/governor-to-call-special-session-on-operation-rio-grande-issues-next-week/ |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = fox13now.com |date = September 13, 2017 }}</ref><ref name="Special Session">{{cite news |title = Herbert to call special session to deal with Operation Rio Grande issues next week – Utah Standard News |url = https://www.utahstandardnews.com/herbert-call-special-session-deal-operation-rio-grande-issues-next-week/ |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = Utah Standard News |date = September 14, 2017 }}</ref>

The operation has led to over 1000 arrests<ref name="1000 Arrests">{{cite news|last1=McKellar|first1=Katie|title=Over 1,000 arrests made in Operation Rio Grande as 37 new treatment beds open {{!}} KSL.com|url=https://www.ksl.com/?sid=45717402&nid=148&title=over-1000-arrests-made-in-operation-rio-grande-as-37-new-treatment-beds-open|accessdate=September 15, 2017|work=KSL.com|date=September 7, 2017|language=en}}</ref> including persons that are homeless, and drug dealers. Agencies participating are the Utah Department of Public Safety, state probation and parole officers, Utah Highway Patrol, social workers, and lawyers. The operation has also led to arrests in [[Ogden, Utah]]. Out of the over 1000 people arrested, 676 non-violent offenders were released because of jail overcrowding, ability to obtain bail or to attend court dates. Most of the charges were for misdemeanors.<ref name="Ogden Raids">{{cite news |last1 = Mims |first1 = Bob |title = SLC's 'Operation Rio Grande' leads to Ogden drug raid, arrests |url = http://www.sltrib.com/news/2017/09/13/slcs-operation-rio-grande-leads-to-ogden-drug-raid-arrests/ |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = The Salt Lake Tribune |date = September 13, 2017 }}</ref> Of the arrestees, 35 have been identified as being eligible for Salt Lake's drug court. One person declined the offer of drug court.<ref name="Drug Court">{{cite news |last1 = Romero |first1 = McKenzie |title = 35 candidates appear in new drug court formed under Operation Rio Grande |url = https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865688728/35-candidates-appear-in-new-drug-court-formed-under-Operation-Rio-Grande.html |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = DeseretNews.com |date = September 13, 2017 |language = en }}</ref><ref name="1023 Arrests">{{cite news |last1 = McKellar |first1 = Katie |title = Over 1,000 arrests made in Operation Rio Grande as 37 new treatment beds open |url = https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865688336/Over-1000-arrests-made-in-Operation-Rio-Grande-as-37-new-treatment-beds-open.html |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = DeseretNews.com |date = September 7, 2017 |language = en }}</ref> Each qualified arrestee must go to a drug bed for long-term addiction treatment. Completion of drug court means that any current and previous drug charges will be expunged from their record.<ref name="37 Beds">{{cite news |last1 = McKellar |first1 = Katie |title = 35 of 1,000 arrested in Operation Rio Grande qualify for 'specialty court' starting this week |url = https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865688584/35-of-1000-arrested-in-operation-qualify-for-specialty-court-starting-this-week.html |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = DeseretNews.com |date = September 11, 2017 |language = en }}</ref>

The purge is causing a spillover into outlying neighborhoods.<ref name="Spillover">{{cite news |last1 = Lawrence |first1 = Danica |title = Some neighbors are frustrated with the impact 'Operation Rio Grande' is having on their neighborhoods |url = http://fox13now.com/2017/08/21/some-neighbors-are-frustrated-with-the-impact-operation-rio-grande-is-having-on-their-neighborhoods/ |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = fox13now.com |date = August 22, 2017 }}</ref> It is also causing spillover into southern Utah and authorities there are worried about collateral impact such as theft, vandalism, loitering, trespassing, drug dealing, public intoxication, and violence.<ref name="Southern Utah">{{cite news |last1 = Bolerjack |first1 = D.J. |title = Operation Rio Grande forcing hundreds of homeless to southern Utah cities |url = http://kutv.com/news/local/operation-rio-grande-forcing-hundreds-of-homeless-to-southern-utah-cities |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = KUTV |date = September 7, 2017 }}</ref>

Utah House Speaker Greg Hughes and Department of Public Safety Commissioner Keith Squires also emphasized that the law enforcement prong of Operation Rio Grande—its name aside—won't be confined to the Rio Grande area. If wrongdoers "run and try to hide at the Jordan River, we're going to the Jordan River. If they're going to South Salt Lake, we're going to South Salt Lake. West Valley—were going there," Hughes said. "This is not about a geographic area, per se, as it is what has hurt this community, the state and the people that live in it. And we're going to eradicate that."<ref name="Operation a Go">{{cite news |last1 = Piper |first1 = Matthew |title = ‘Operation Rio Grande’ launched near homeless shelter with arrests, big jump in police presence |url = http://www.sltrib.com/news/2017/08/14/operation-rio-grande-crackdown-near-homeless-shelter-now-underway/ |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = The Salt Lake Tribune |date = August 14, 2017 }}</ref><ref name="Calvin Jolley">{{cite news |last1 = Jolley |first1 = Calvin |title = Commentary: Operation Rio Grande is driven by fearmongering |url = http://www.sltrib.com/opinion/commentary/2017/09/09/commentary-operation-rio-grande-is-driven-by-fearmongering/ |accessdate = September 15, 2017 |work = The Salt Lake Tribune |date = September 9, 2017 }}</ref>

The house speaker, and also Utah Lieutenant Governor Spencer Cox estimate the two year cost of the operation to be $67{{nbsp}}million.<ref name="67 Million">{{cite news |last1 = Winslow |first1 = Ben |title = The price tag for Operation Rio Grande? $67 million |url = http://fox13now.com/2017/08/28/the-price-tag-for-operation-rio-grande-67-million/ |accessdate = September 16, 2017 |work = fox13now.com |date = August 28, 2017 }}</ref>

